title: For Sale:  Ruger M77 Mark II, 7mm Rem Mag, Left-Handed Bolt w/ Extras!
postcontent: For sale is my Ruger M77 Mark II, chambered in 7mm Remington Magnum.  This particular rifle was manufactured in 1999 and features a beautiful grey laminate stock, all stainless steel parts (24" barrel, action, left-handed bolt, etc.), and a professionally mounted (sighted in at 200 yds) Buckmaster 3-9x40 scope with amber see-through, flip-up eyepiece covers.  I'm also including everything pictured in the photo including a bipod, sling, and brand new 48" Allen soft rifle case.  Also included, but not pictured are 3 boxes of factory 7mm ammunition containing the following: (20) rounds of Remington Core-Lokt 150 grain soft point, (14) rounds of Fusion 150 grain soft point, and (17) rounds of Fusion 175 grain soft point.  Additional information:The Ruger M77 is a bolt-action rifle first produced by Sturm, Ruger, & Company in 1968. It was designed by Jim Sullivan during his three years with Ruger. The rifle features a traditional Mauser-style two-lugged bolt with a claw extractor.  The M77 was retooled almost entirely and reintroduced in 1991 as the Mark II. The safety, bolt, and trigger were completely redesigned. The claw extractor was retained, but the bolt face was opened up to allow controlled-round feeding. The plunger ejector was replaced with a Mauser style blade ejector. Finally, a three-position safety allowed the bolt to be operated while the gun was still on safe, making unloading of the rifle less hazardous. Ruger also eliminated the adjustable trigger that came stock on the original M77.  Perhaps the most novel feature of the M77 is the only one that has not been redesigned, the angled action screw. The front action screw of traditional bolt-action rifles draws the receiver directly down against the stock. The M77 uses an angled screw that draws the action down and to the rear, tightly bedding it against the stock.This is an outstanding and unique rifle.  It is used but in excellent condition.CONDITIONS OF SALE:Buyer arranges and pays all FFL transfer fees IN ADDITION to the sale price.Face-to-face deals ONLY. FFL transfer MUST take place in Oregon. I am NOT willing to ship out of state.Only cash will be accepted. Payment is due in full at the time of transfer. No trades. No exceptions.
